  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">David Lee Child thinks that Maria Weston Chapman does not do justice &quot;to our strong-hearted James S. Gibbons.&quot; Child feels a great respect for him. Child said: &quot;I am going to publish a set of interrogatories adapted to most elections.&quot; He thinks it wrong to have been so indolent and distrustful &quot;about this instrumentality.&quot; He comments on the fire kindled by Edward Everett&apos;s reply. &quot;It flared up to the teror and dismay of the slavemongers. When a candidate has answered our letters favorably, he becomes an object of suspicion &amp; proscription with them.&quot; Child is thinking with secret satisfaction of the Philadelphia meeting. Abby Kelley denounces him as a &quot;traitor in all but &apos;overt acts.&apos;&quot;</subfield>
